<br>
As fate would have it I had some time to reflect on this discussion and have reached a point where I think it all needs to be pulled together and presented in a functional mode.  I’ve decided to break this down into different categories; I’ll try to keep it cogent but I can get ‘off on a tangent’ and I know it…I’ve tried to boil it all down into ‘how it has to operate’ functionally and then linked it as much as possible to our onscreen knowledge of Nietzscheans, but forgive if I fail to correlate it completely to what we have seen on-screen.  I think the information was valuable in its own right and therefore I am presenting it. If future episodes contradict what I present here, well <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>{Cait’s ego}</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> they goofed!! <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>{Cait’s ego}</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Throughout the hours of research that I have done, during all the incarnations of this discussion, I have come to the realization that <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>matriarchy</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> is no simple term to define. Perhaps because there is no agreement that one ever existed but perhaps because we ultimately misunderstand what the power dynamics in such a society would be and if we cannot imagine the existence of such a way of life, we cannot suspend disbelief long enough to here/see the story in front of, now can we? Although there seems to be a general consensus as to the meaning of the word, it is extremely difficult to derive a single group of criteria, which could be used to outline the essentials of a matriarchal society. That said, here is what I imagine to be true and how I think it relates to my favorite ‘Nietzschean’ guys.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> Introduction: </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
In patriarchies, there are apparently always three things conspicuously that are absent in matriarchies: an elite, wealth and destitute poverty side by side, and social class. What is more, matriarchal societies are NOT based on the institution of property, a state of affairs patriarchists have difficulty even envisioning.  They are based on <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>KINSHIP</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> The difficulty is that when a man thinks of matriarchy, he thinks of a patriarchy with women in the place of men; he does not stop to consider that matriarchy may be a complete mirror-image. Where patriarchy establishes law, matriarchy establishes custom; where patriarchy establishes military power, matriarchy establishes religious authority; where patriarchy encourages the aresteia of he individual warrior, matriarchy encourages the tradition bound cohesion of the collective.&quot; &quot; (Thompson, W.I. (1981) The Time Falling Bodies Take To Light; St. Martin’s Press: New York p. 140)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
People often think of matriarchal societies as if they were merely a matter of role-reversal with patriarchal ones, except that women were the bosses - in fact, women in such societies had the primary place but this was probably as part of a genuinely egalitarian society, such as is known in several Native American cultures and African Cultures. <br>
<br>
<br>
Anthropologist Peggy Reeves Sanday <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> After years of research among the Minangkabau people of West Sumatra, Indonesia, she has accepted that group's own self-labeling, as a &quot;matriarchate,&quot; or matriarchy. The problem, she asserts, lies in Western cultural notions of what a matriarchy &quot;should&quot; look like—patriarchy's female-twin. <br>
<br>
&quot;Too many anthropologists have been looking for a society where women rule the affairs of everyday life, including government,&quot; she said. &quot;That template—and a singular, Western perspective on power—doesn't fit very well when you're looking at non-Western cultures like the Minangkabau. In West Sumatra, males and females relate more like partners for the common good than like competitors ruled by egocentric self-interest. Social prestige accrues to those who promote good relations by following the dictates of custom and religion.&quot;   <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
 <br>
In societies led by women, or &quot;matriarchies,&quot; there are vastly different rules governing sexuality and marriage, property inheritance, and the distribution of power than those rules operative in societies led by men, or &quot;patriarchies.&quot; When women have greater social control than men, less stringent social sanctions are imposed on female sexual activities and choice of partners. Illegitimacy is absent, and inheritance and descent are organized through female ancestors.   <br>
<br>
Briefly, (well, maybe not so briefly) women enjoy high status under the following circumstances: (the more power in these areas of course the more status a woman holds, conversely the less power she has in these areas the less status she holds)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Economic Level: Societies of Reciprocity </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>It is thought that if Matriarchies existed at all they were most likely agricultural societies in which women had control over the means of production although I’m not in complete agreement with this hypothesis.  All that really needs to exist for women to administrate economically in a culture, is their dominance in the areas of production that contribute directly to daily life and well-being. (examples; Food production, medicine, education, household goods, etc)  Goods would then be distributed according to egalitarian systems that were identical to the lines of kinship and the patterns of marriage. The advantages and disadvantages concerning the acquisition of goods would be adjusted by social rules and modified by exigent circumstances.  If wealth begins to accumulate in certain areas of the society, rituals of redistribution take place.  (For example, a local festival would be organized in which wealthy families are obliged to distribute their riches to all inhabitants of the village) For this they gain great honor and prestige. And in large families where one faction might prosper over another, goods and services would be re-distributed through the Matriarch for the benefit of her entire family.  Extending this theory to an entire Pride (which might also be tied by blood and marriage lines) and you have the economic control resting in the hands of the Matriarch of a Pride.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
All the on-screen evidence points to Prides being dominated by lines of kinship/marriage and all the non-canon evidence supports this notion as well.  <br>
<br>
Orca Pride: The men appeared to be responsible for defense and protection in DH and IP, it would follow that all the establishment of living quarters and the distribution of resources would fall to the Matriarch and the available adults (women) given the males are involved in all the things necessary to protect the pride form their enemies. Olma when she offered the Alphaship to Tyr, as much as said, ‘all you have to do is lead us and deliver us from our enemies and I will do the rest’. Although she did not say the ‘I’ll do the rest’ it certainly was implied and it gives us a good indication as to what her ‘duties’ are within a Pride. <br>
<br>
I thought when I saw it that we had in front of us an excellent indication of the division of power between men and women. In any event, we might have a modern day (Sci-Fi) version of an agricultural society with men doing the hunting/protecting and women gathering resources/food.  <br>
<br>
According to all the resources I found on the subject this is actually the exact situation conducive to a Matriarchal society because it gives women the responsibility/power over the accumulation of resources.  What I have not found in any research until recently is any insight into how and why men would continue to allow such a division of power.   <br>
<br>
One of the questions that has been haunting me since the inception of this discussion was how could women maintain power given that men are aggressive, competitive and could by sheer strength of willpower, usurp the power of women.  <br>
<br>
Well, the answer was so simple and was staring me in the face the whole time. It is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>the control of resources and economics.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The importance of this economic control is far reaching and because of this, women control the men to an extent. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Cait will concede that this can only remain true as long as the defense of the Pride remains a constant issue.<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  A hostile environment is the exact environment where gender specific roles will develop because the physical strength and power of men is always needed in the defense of the Pride/Clan/Family.  <br>
<br>
It is only when day-to-day life becomes less hostile that men begin to usurp the roles of women and become ‘gatherers’.  BUT given Nietzschean philosophy and physiology, the idea of a Nietzschean males taking on roles tantamount to ‘gathering’ seems more implausible to me than the idea of an actual Matriarchy.  Men would become complacent in sedentary or ‘gathering’ roles.  They simple are too safe and would not garner a male any honor grandiose enough to enable him to be ‘chosen’ to mate! So I have conclude that given all the philosophical and biological imperatives Nietzscehans have been indoctrinated with over countless centuries the only way to maintain any wealth is to have women administer over affairs of commerce.   Add to this all the evidence on screen and in the Systems Library indicates that hostile environments are the ‘order of the day’ for Nietzscehans and perhaps it is designed for some very specific reasons in addition to ‘species adaptability’.<br>
<br>
Nietzscehans, we have one direct and one indirect cause for the existence of the dangerous environments; one is the Post-Fall landscape in general and the other is the premise of Nietzschean development in the first place.  The location of the original colony was chosen because it was so hostile.  <br>
<br>
This leads me to believe that it was not only chosen to ensure Darwinian ‘natural selection’ but was also chosen to preserve gender specific roles.  In other words the hostile environment itself ensures women maintain their power because men are too busy in traditional hunter/defensive roles.  <br>
<br>
I hadn’t quite put that one together… How they interact and how one maintains the other.  It’s reciprocal when viewed in this manner.  It also might explain the absence of a ‘Golden Age’ for Nietzscheans because their culture is predicated on hostile environments to maintain a gender balance of power as well as natural selection.  All in all it is a self-renewing system that reinforces itself each and every day, with each and every generation.  It isn’t just that they all agreed to conduct their lives this way back in the beginning;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> <br>
(Although consensus was needed, but Cait will get to that later)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> it is that the lives they lead, require that women function within their own areas in powerful and authorative ways because the men are not available for these roles.  No one allows, no one dominates per se, the structure of the environment itself dictates the distribution of power and the implementation of economic modes of acquisition. <br>
