<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Research revealed that on the social level, (in Matriarchal societies) people lived in clans that are formed according to the principle of matrilineality in which kinship; clan names, social positions, and political titles are passed on through the female line.   The women live permanently in the clan house of their mothers, since they are not required to move to the homes of their husbands. Women control the sources of nourishment and have the power of disposition over the goods of the clan, which ensures their strong social position. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>This distinguishes a matriarchal society from one that is only matrilineal.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Other reasons for high female status were that women had economic power due to inheritance, and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>the residence pattern lent itself to female solidarity.]</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Women remain in the homes of their mothers and sisters.  Women they have grown up with their entire lives and with whom they have a bond of blood.  This promotes a greater degree of solidarity than for the woman who marries and goes to live in the home of her husband.  In monogamous marriages, the woman is now alone with no power and in polygamous marriages she is one of many women she is unfamiliar with.  In the later example bonds can of course be forged, but so can enmity.  Keeping the resources of women and their accumulated wealth in one location (clan-home) ensures the <br>
continuation of the family and the line.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  <br>
Everything we have seen on screen supports the fact that the women are primarily focused on the continuation of their families.  We have to date not seen 2 wives interact.  We have DH as a reference to # of wives, but we are unclear on the living arrangements.  So the proposition of a mother-ruled clan-home is not in any contradiction to existing canon.  <br>
<br>
I’ve stated before that I felt the wives of the men did not live in the same house <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(for what Cait believes are obvious reasons)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and I think this description gives us reason to believe that indeed Prides would be set up as matri-clans.<br>
<br>
It also gives us a good idea of how the Matriarch comes to power.  The eldest woman, with the largest extended family, and the woman who controls the greatest resources would be an ideal candidate.  Her reign as Matriarch would depend upon how she distributes those resources but any leader has responsibilities to those they lead.  I’m sure that alliances would be formed for survival reasons and for purposes of security, but generally I can see from what we saw in Orca Pride that this could follow.  Olma’s power over the men of Orca Pride could very well be because she is the ‘First’ woman/mother, and the woman each and every <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>other woman</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> in the Pride listens to.  Consider if all the men of the pride were either blood relatives or married to blood relatives of Olma how that could affect the power dynamic of the men within a Pride.  <br>
<br>
Given that all the resources would be controlled by the women, that all the women remain in the mother’s home and that women control mating privileges, it gives us (well Cait at least) a better idea of how power is distributed and maintained.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(Now, Cait admits that this does not explain the function of mothers in larger Prides, where there might be 100’s of families within a pride.  But they might be set up in a series of extended family-type groups, who knows we haven’t seen larger Prides in anything but combat scenarios.  But it could be explained within this context as well)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->   <br>
<br>
Also, it occurred to me that all of these social conditions would of course be modified by the living conditions of each Pride.  The Prides with more permanent living arrangements might be able to adhere to the ‘clan home’ type thing, while Prides that were nomadic might not have this type of arrangement.  I also considered the possibility that we’ve (Cait) been looking at this from a very restricted viewpoint, giving no latitude in execution.  In other words, we’ve dismissed the entire idea of a matriarchy just because it ‘broke one of the rules’.  Which is of course not the way things actually operate in RL at all because nothing in our real lives or on TV adheres to all the cultural ‘rules’ dictated by any culture.  I don’t know why I fell into the trap of looking for absolutes, but I admit that I did.  No absolutes need exist for Matriarchal societies to operate any more than absolutes need exist in Patriarchal societies.<br>
<br>
If we look at existing social institutions there are always exceptions to what is deemed to be ‘ideal’.  Since Nietzscheans are human in origin, I’m sure they would have as many variations in social conduct as we currently have on just our planet. (Probably more) What does remain are the gender specific roles.  And before I am lambasted about gender specific roles, I’d like to state categorically and for the record that there are real and genuine gender specific roles.  We cannot avoid some of them because they are specific to gender.  <br>
<br>
Women do the birthing of children and while women of course deserve the choice as to how, when and where and why they reproduce, they are the ones who do it.  It is a gender specific role.  Men are physically stronger than women and because they are not required to give birth and nurture young (breast feed babies) they are certainly freer to move about unrestricted.  But (yes, even men) men certainly deserve the right to determine how, when, where and why their strength is used, but it is gender specific.  <br>
<br>
From all I can see Nietzscehans have accepted these gender specific roles and used the strengths of each gender towards a specific goal. As a matter of fact once I thought (long and hard) about it, Nietzscehans are very open and matter-of-fact regarding gender-specific roles; the roles that only a fool would argue about because they are specific to biology.   Making a fuss about the choices regarding women having babies or not having babies would be nonsense to a Nietzschean because that is what women do.  What would there be to discuss, especially since she gets to determine the who, what, where and when of her own reproduction.  And likewise it would be nonsense to a Nietzschean to make a fuss about who is going to ‘go into battle’ because it would of course be the person who would win the battle.  These two concepts would not be attributed to any philosophy or doctrine because they reside in biologically defined roles.  BUT nowhere have we seen that these roles are THE ONLY ROLES EITHER GENDER ENGAGES IN!!<br>
<br>
What we can only suppose is that a species dedicated to survival and pragmatic and adaptable in the extreme would stop at just gender specific roles.  Any culture expects its citizens to develop the other talents any individual might have that are NOT GENDER SPECIFIC.  Since we have only seen Nietzschean men and women in their gender-specific roles we cannot judge at this point how much freedom their might be to pursue other life styles.  But we have nothing that suggests they cannot either.  <br>
<br>
In Tunnel we have a high-ranking Admiral who ostensibly (could have been faulty intelligence) had no wives or children and yet he apparently is not suffering any stigma in his military career. However we do not know if he is fertile or sterile, and military honors alone are not the honors a Nietzschean man would seek.  Military successes would be the ‘feats’ to impress the ‘chicks’. (Thank you Beka) OTOH, Quchera in USV was a sterile woman not just a woman who didn’t want to have any children, so it is not really indicative of the choices open to women who are fertile and who wish to postpone or delay motherhood.  I think QT was on point when she said that Quchera was speaking as a woman outside the benefits of her own culture and had a case of ‘sour grapes’.  Who knows what she would have chosen had she been fertile and not ostracized from everything a Nietzschean would hold dear.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>How much power can men have and a society still be a matriarchy?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Well, how much power can women have and a society still be a Patriarchy?  In a Matriarchy, what if women hold the power in politics and in the home, but men are the religious or military leaders? What if a society appears to be governed by men, but there is evidence that women are controlling from the shadows?  Ultimately the degree of matriarchy would vary as much as the degree of patriarchy does on our own planet.  Each culture in our own RL could symbolically be viewed as a Pride, and viewed in this context we can see quite easily how the ‘rules’ could change from Pride to Pride just as they change from country to country and culture to culture.  <br>
<br>
