<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Here's a thought that came to me last weekend. We spoke before about the problems of freeing the oppressed class into the existing society. The basic structure of the society doesn't change, and so free or no, the power structure doesn't change. This is true on a political/social level. But it is also true on a psychological level. We forget how much of a psychological investment the oppressed often have in the existing power structure. {Emphasis added}<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Their understanding of self-validation is framed in the existing power structure relationships</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> {Emphasis added}. It is the classic distinction between reform and revolution. The power structure supports reform in order to quell revolution. But also, the oppressed favor reform, because it gives them the perceived ability to be validated by the existing rules. Why overthrow the economic system just when I'm getting ready to be rich? Likewise, why overthrow the matriarchy when I'm getting ready to have 3 or 4 very high ranking wives? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
