<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>On the cultural level, matriarchal societies have a complex religious system <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>that should not be characterized as a &quot;fertility cult&quot;.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The fundamental concept expressed in myths, rituals, and spiritual customs is the concrete belief in rebirth. Every person knows that after death she or he will be reborn as a child into the same clan. Women in matriarchal societies are greatly respected for their ability to give birth to the ancestors and to renew the life of the clan.  The cosmos is perceived as the Great Goddess of Heaven and all Creation. It is she who gives birth to the stars in the east and allows them to move over the sky (her celestial body) until they return to her in the west through her power of death. <br>
<br>
The matriarchal concept of the human and natural worlds lacks the dualistic, patriarchal way of thinking that separates &quot;nature&quot; from &quot;culture.&quot; Furthermore, it lacks the dualistic concept of morality that defines what is &quot;good&quot; and splits off what is &quot;evil.&quot;  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>From the matriarchal perspective, life brings forth death, and death brings forth life again in its own time.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The opposition of &quot;good&quot; and &quot;evil&quot; makes no sense in a Matriarchy. In the same way, the female and the male are a cosmic polarity, it would never occur to matriarchal people to regard one sex as inferior to or weaker than the other, as is common in patriarchal societies. In that non-dualistic view of the world, no principal distinction is made between time profane and the sacred. <br>
<br>
As an aside note***I found that it is because of this spirituality that the women were/are able to develop the philosophies needed for the institution of a clan structure. This is very important in the structure clan/pride systems because it is the women who develop the sense of a structured family in the first place, taking that concept and expanding it to extended family and related kin.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  <br>
<br>
Since everything we have seen regarding Nietzscheans supports the idea of life and death and re-birth, I found this to be the most revealing in relationship to the idea of Nietzschean Spirituality.  Since we are primarily dominated in our world by Patriarchal Religions it was difficult to imagine Nietzschean Spirituality.  But here again, perhaps we are looking for signs that we can recognize as spiritual.  Who among us knows all of the religious practices of every religion and cult in the world, I am sure some of the practices and beliefs we would not recognize as religious or spiritual, but they are to the people who believe in them.  What we do have is evidence that a particular belief system does exist.  We have on screen testimony that (for what ever reason) the bones are the only things a Nietzschean would die for.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Strong words considering the entire premise of the culture is to stay alive at all costs.. </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->We’ve seen that some believe it more than others, but this is natural and is certainly more understandable than to dismiss their spirituality out of hand because we cannot believe that these people could believe in something other than themselves.  <br>
<br>
Given the fact that matriarchal societies are grounded in the present, with birth and death as recurring themes, I can now easily see how Nietzschean spiritual beliefs could be grounded in the concepts of birth, death and re-birth and why the women would be at the center of such a spiritual view.  Given the pre-occupation with the return of Drago through countless cycles of birth, death and re-birth, it takes on even more significance.  Add to this Nietzsche’s premise of <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>‘Eternal Recurrence’:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> My philosophy brings the triumphant idea of which all other modes of thought will ultimately perish. It is the great cultivating idea: the races that cannot bear it stand condemned; those who find it the greatest benefit are chosen to rule... <br>
I want to teach the idea that gives many the right to erase themselves - the great cultivating idea... <br>
<br>
Everything becomes and recurs eternally - escape is impossible! - Supposing we could judge value, what follows? The idea of recurrence as a selective principle, in the service of strength (and barbarism!!)... <br>
<br>
To endure the idea of the recurrence one needs: freedom from morality; new means against the fact of pain ( pain conceived as a tool, as the father of pleasure...); the enjoyment of all kinds of uncertainty, experimentalism, as a counterweight to this extreme fatalism; abolition of the concept of necessity; abolition of the &quot;will&quot;; abolition of &quot;knowledge-in-itself.&quot;  ~ Nietzsche</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Given the Spirituality of Matriarchal societies and Nietzsche’s theme of Eternal Recurrence we now can see it all fits quite nicely into what we have seen and heard about the Nietzschean belief system.  It is NOT grounded in a belief in a ‘Supreme Being’ at all; it has at the core of it the very real themes of real life and existence (Family, marriage, progeny and the eternal cycle of birth, life, and death recurring over and over again). It also would explain the reverence for the role of motherhood, the insistence on a particular mating ritual, (Cait has more on this in Part 5) and the honor in the roles of husband and father, because these are the mystical roles that we can actually see in our daily lives. They are not vested in some ‘mythical’ place of paradise where good and evil are judged, no they reside in the very real life roles of mother and father and the eternal birth of future mothers and fathers.  These roles in and of themselves are Spiritual by nature in a matriarchal society.  .<br>
