<br>
In all my research I hadn’t come across any theory that adequately addressed the mating ritual of Nietzscheans.  While it is nice to think of the ritual as a representation of power for the women, it just wasn’t enough for me.  Strictly speaking and from a completely Darwinian viewpoint, it <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>is</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> essential to have women making the mating choices regardless of the relative strength of men to take mating privileges from them, but I still couldn’t understand the principles involved.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>exogamic adj 1: reproduced by fusion of gametes of different ancestries 2: of marriage outside a class or tribe as required by custom or law.<br>
<br>
Exogamous: A marriage between two people of different groups is exogamous. Any individual belongs to many different groups, defined by different variables.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is perhaps the most important issue when speaking of a Nietzscehans Matriarchy as opposed to a Nietzschean Patriarchy (Which is of course what it would be if it is not a Matriarchy, isn’t it?)  A woman retaining the choice over who to mate with is at the very core of the ultimate survival of any species.  <br>
<br>
In human nature we have man predisposed to deposit his seed in as many places as possible, hence the competition for mates is viable among males because they are in fact seeking to capture as many as possible in order to increase their chances of off-spring. This is in the hard wiring of males to do so.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>I am NOT speaking of morality here; I am speaking of biology.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I don’t want to get off on a tangent about male bashing when I am not doing so.  (Just a little preemptive strike here)  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(Cait would agree that any thinking man could of course refrain from the ‘need’ to seek multiple partners in favor of the cultural choices he has made, but Cait would like to point out that she is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>not</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> talking about morality or cultural prohibitions, she is talking about building a culture on existing biological imperatives and using biologically ‘normal’ behavior as the guideline for a culture.  Not the use of culture to re-direct/re-define ‘normal’ biological behavior.  This is an important distinction that I want to make clear at the outset, because I don’t want to fall into a discussion about cultural defined morality and behavior.  Not because it is not an interesting subject, it is, but because Nietzscheans are all about rising above culturally defined ‘anythings’ and seeking their own ‘will’ in the expression of their lives.  Cait therefore thinks we should limit the discussion to how all of this relates to Nietzscheans, OK? Cait is pleading here!) </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->     <br>
<br>
Given the disposition of men towards multiple partners in order to reach as many females as possible in his reproductive quest it makes absolute sense to award Nietzschean men with as many partners as would choose him.   There is no benefit in restricting his behavior because that is at cross-purposes to a male being ‘who he is’ and Drago would have known this.  Why pretend this does not exist when it does?  Why not accept it as a norm instead of deviant?  I think above all, these people are all about being exactly who they are, and this would have been the premise of the experiment originally.  Per Nietzsche, strip away all the ‘rules’ and ‘now you’re supposed to’s’ then who are we really?  <br>
<br>
When it comes to women, their biological imperatives are much different (as we all know) because women are not driven by the same agenda.  Reproductive choices for women are more selective.  Why?  Because women have (sorry to be so direct, well not really) one egg that needs fertilizing.  She has a limited span of years to reproduce in, long gestation periods, extended nurturing needed for offspring and her needs are different during this process.  So, women due to these necessities are selective in their mating choices.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(Cait now wants to avoid another discussion about women who appear not to be selective in our culture… Firstly, behavior is like a bell curve so there will be exceptions. And secondly, the choices we see other women make, may appear unwise within a culturally defined paradigm, but not in a biological one.  Research shows that women make mating choices based on some strictly physical cues; strong legs and buttocks in a male are strong mating cues for females. So for the purposes of this discussion, Cait is referring only to biological imperatives, not culturally defined morality, OK?  Once again Cait is pleading!</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
So, men seek multiple partners with little discrimination and women will seek out a specific mate.  Seems like a paradox to me, but that is just me!  But apparently Drago figured it all out because Nietzschean culture seems to take this all into account.  Males are in fact allowed multiple mates, thus satisfying their mating instincts and women are allowed to choice whomever they please, even if he is already ‘taken’ thus making her first choice always available to her.  Of course consensus is needed between mates but, that is a given.  Now we have a mating practice that fits each genders mating imperatives. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Cait will admit that this is a most difficult area to address, but she also is aware now, that this is because this is the most heavily influenced area of all of our lives when it comes to behavior and morality.  Most of the taboos and restrictions we encounter in our daily lives center around sexual behavior, so this area would be the most difficult to address in terms of different mating practices.  That said, it does not discount the facts as they present in each gender, even here on Earth.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Now relating biological norms to exogamous marriages and why Cait feels this leads to a Matriarchy, I think that the women have to be in control in order to allow diversity into the gene pool.  We have Freya choosing Tyr (who to Orca Pride is an outsider, despite being Nietzschean) and Olma approving.  This is more than just a woman making mating choices and the Matriarchy approving, it is much more significant.  <br>
<br>
What it says is that women can mate outside their Pride and bring ‘new’ men into the Pride.  If Pride life were a patriarchy, the men who ruled would never allow outsiders to come into their Pride without approval because they could be threat to their authority and power base.  If it were a patriarchy there would probably be taboos against marriages outside of the Pride for these very reasons.  Keeping men and resources under the control of the dominant male (in a Patriarchy) is accomplished in many ways, but one of the most effective ways is to limit the mating choices of the ‘females’ in order to avoid stronger males into any group.  <br>
<br>
But because it is a Matriarchy and the choices of the women regarding mating are sacrosanct, they are free to mate with outsiders, thus accomplishing exactly what Drago and Darwin intended (IMHO), genetic diversity.  Since the men have no say in these marriages to outsiders, they also cannot control the new influx of competition (via new males) that would accompany these outsiders into a Pride.  Women would of course be making choices based upon whatever strengths they were looking for in particular and these new strengths would be brought into the Pride through the man and his subsequent offspring.  This ensures the continual competition among the men because no single man every ‘corners’ the market, so to speak, because he cannot control the pool of males the women have to draw upon.  Only in a Matriarchy could any of this occur because men who ruled would never allow stronger men into their group.  They would limit the mating choices of women exactly the way they do in our own culture.  <br>
<br>
Take a look at all of the taboos in almost any culture that is run by males and you will find some cultural or moral prohibition against marrying outsiders for women.  Of course in a Patriarchy there is no such taboo against a man mating with an outsider.  Thus in a Patriarchy a power base is maintained in the ruling class and the women are prohibited from mating with anyone outside of the dominant class/culture/race/ethnic group/etc…….<br>
<br>
But in the Nietzschean world we have on screen conformation that women can marry outsiders and need only the approval of the Matriarch.  Freya even stated the very reason for it, “We need some new DNA” being completely aware of her own biological imperatives, she made her choice freely even though there was a battle in progress.  Had I not done so much research and ‘thinking’ about these people, I might have missed the significance of that scene because it was more than the fact that she could stop the altercation.  She could invite a stronger male into the Pride, to live and breed!  No, this could only happen in a Matriarchy where women ruled more than just their own choices for mate.  At the very least they would have to rule the social order and more probably they would also have control over all of the areas mentioned in the earlier sections. (to some degree at least)<br>
<br>
Here is what I think ultimately makes this work and why there might not be any need to worry about the power of the women being usurped to any great degree. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> (Although of course it could be, there are description in Ancestor’ Breath that strike a cord with me concerning males gaining more influence and power.  The significant inbreeding [remaining within a Pride only to mate] the tendency towards monogamy are all signs that males had more influence, but this is another discussion I think)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p>____________________________________<br>
