I needed to come back to this.   Actually, human males are NOT able to nurse babies.  Though men have some of the same underlying mammary tissue, it is not functional, and there is not enough of it.   Though there have been theories advanced as to why men have ANY mammary gland-like structures underlying their breasts, the simplest answer is simply that males and females start out exactly the same in the womb, their gene structure, and hormones causing sex differentiation using the same materials to make either a boy or a girl.  Sex differentiation is an important part of what makes human beings human beings. In any event - as a mom who nursed for two years, I can say that female breasts are uniquely structured for the job.  Females are more fatty - which is important to create the right kind of milk, females breasts protrude, which give babies an easy target... female breasts position babies at just the right distance from the mother to allow imprinting to happen based on baby's field of vision, female breasts allow latching on - by virtue of their shape... Evolutionarily, we allocated our resources to create specialists -female specialists and male specialists - androgeny doesn't work for us.<br>
<br>
In the few cases where males do have lactation capabilities - it is most often a result of something going wrong in their hormone or chromosomal structure.  I've seen males like this - they are rather unfortunately circumstanced - their breasts developing somewhat like adolescent girls...<br>
<br>
There are a very few mammals for whom it IS true that males can take over the lactating functions in absence of a female, but human beings aren't one of them.  And even in those species - the male takeover is inferior to the original female function.  <br>
<br>
